lobbying_activities:
[{'general_issue_code': 'NAT', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Natural Resources', 'description': 'H.R.____ (DeFazio): Opposed bill that would effectively privatize our federal forest lands by creating legally binding fiduciary trusts for the sole purpose of providing revenues to counties. The result would be industrialized clearcuts across the landscape as this would be the most efficient way to meet obligations to maximize revenues. Industrialization of public lands will damage watersheds and pollute drinking water, putting our western water supply at risk, as over 50% of fresh water supplies in the West come from federal forests. Intensive logging and other extractive practices dumps sediment into rivers, that can increase costs for local water utilities, cause erosion and can alter the timing of water availability. (H.R. ___, DeFazio) would sidestep or limit the application of the Endangered Species Act (ESA) or the Clean Water Act.
Bureau of Land Management O&C Lands: In general educated and lobbied for proposals to uphold the Northwest Forest Plan, Endangered Species Act, National Environmental Policy Act, Clean Water Act protections and for ecologically sound forest management.

S. _________ (Wyden) To restore forest landscapes, protect old growth forests, and manage national forests in the eastside forests of the State of Oregon, and for other purposes. Lobbied for passage of this bill.', 'foreign_entity_issues': '', 'lobbyists': [{'lobbyist': {'id': 52277, 'prefix': None, 'prefix_display': None, 'first_name': 'RANDI', 'nickname': None, 'middle_name': None, 'last_name': 'SPIVAK', 'suffix': None, 'suffix_display': None}, 'covered_position': 'VP Government Affairs', 'new': False}], 'government_entities': [{'id': 2, 'name': 'HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES'}, {'id': 1, 'name': 'SENATE'}, {'id': 212, 'name': 'U.S. Forest Service'}]}]

lobbying_activities:
[{'general_issue_code': 'AGR', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Agriculture', 'description': "H.R. 1947, Federal Agriculture Reform and Risk Management Act of 2013 and S. 954, Agriculture Reform, Food and Jobs Act Act (e.g., FARM Bill) -- WTA lobbied in support of the Department of Agriculture's Rural Utilities Service's Broadband Loan Program, which enables rural local exchange carriers (RLECs) to secure funds to build telecommunications infrastructure capable of delivering broadband in rural areas.", 'foreign_entity_issues': '', 'lobbyists': [{'lobbyist': {'id': 43752, 'prefix': 'mr', 'prefix_display': 'MR.', 'first_name': 'DERRICK', 'nickname': None, 'middle_name': 'B', 'last_name': 'OWENS', 'suffix': None, 'suffix_display': None}, 'covered_position': None, 'new': False}, {'lobbyist': {'id': 37355, 'prefix': None, 'prefix_display': None, 'first_name': 'ERIC', 'nickname': None, 'middle_name': None, 'last_name': 'KEBER', 'suffix': None, 'suffix_display': None}, 'covered_position': None, 'new': False}], 'government_entities': [{'id': 23, 'name': 'Agriculture, Dept of (USDA)'}, {'id': 53, 'name': 'Federal Communications Commission (FCC)'}, {'id': 2, 'name': 'HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES'}, {'id': 1, 'name': 'SENATE'}]}, {'general_issue_code': 'TEC', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Telecommunications', 'description': 'Universal Service and Intercarrier Compensation Reform -- WTA lobbied on the effects the Federal Communications Commission's 2011 Transformation Order is having on rural local exchange carriers (RLECs) and their abilities to continue to build out and modernize their networks to meet their consumers' telecommunications and broadband needs.  Our efforts have also focused on proposed fixes to provisions within the 2011 Order that would provide RLECs with more certainty and predictability to allow them to obtain public (Rural Utilities Service) and private financing to extend broadband in rural areas.

USF Support for Data-Only Broadband -- WTA lobbied on the reasons why RLECs should be able to seek USF support for data-only or "standalone" broadband.  We also discussed why this would be helpful to expanding broadband availability and making broadband more affordable for consumers. 

USF Contributions Reform -- WTA lobbied on the need for the FCC to address how individuals contribute into the Universal Service Fund.  We lobbied on the benefits that reform would bring and why it is important to do so.

Evolution of the Public Switched Telecommunications Network from TDM-to-Internet Protocol (IP) -- WTA discussed how RLECs have been transitioning their current Time-Division Multiplexing (TDM) networks to ones that are becoming more IP-based.  We also shared specific experiences that RLECs are having with this transition.

Rural Call Completion -- WTA lobbied on the problems RLECs and their customers are experiencing as a result of originating carriers' calls outside of rural areas not being completed in RLEC areas. Also support lifting the  Tiahrt and other gun research and policy riders on the annual appropriations bills. 
H.R. 1565 --  the gun background check legislation.S.347/HR 137:  Fix gun check act of 2013: To ensure that all individuals who should be prohibited from buying a firearm are listed in the national instant criminal background check system and require a background check for every firearm sale.

S.150/HR 437: Assault Weapons Ban of 2013: To regulate assault weapons, to ensure that the right to keep and bear arms is not unlimited, and for other purposes.

S.691/HR 138: Large Capacity Ammunition Feeding Device Act: To prohibit the transfer or possession of large capacity ammunition feeding devices, and for other purposes.

S.54/S.179/HR 452: Stop Illegal Trafficking in Firearms Act of 2013: A bill to increase public safety by punishing and deterring firearms trafficking.

Support transition to revised Medicare DSH policy

Support a long-term patch or full repeal of the Sustainable Growth Rate for Physician payments in Medicare

Oppose the proposal of lowering Medicare reimbursements to Inpatient Rehabilitation Facilities.
